Buddies from Nam we would love to see again<br><br>
There was always someone, both dead and alive which we would love to see again.<br>
Sometimes they rotated back and we failed to get their real name or address. Or for some reason we never got around to it, but they made an impact in our lives, saved us from danger or just were there at the right time. We or they rotated back and never got a chance to speak to them again,. <br>
This thread is dedicated to them. Its here we can say, what we never said before, or perhaps just write something about why that person that we may have only known by a nickname , meant so much.<br><br>
Did I ever tell you about tired Aggie? Steven Aguilar.<br>
Was San Pedro, Californian, drove a chevy with twice pipes, I think he went to Wilmington High School Anyways I have tried to contact him but have been unsuccessful.<br><br>
Aggie volunteered for Guns, and he belonged. He became my A-gunner. We did a lot of crazy things together. Once we ripped off a six-by truck and drove it into battalion cause someone told us they were serving hamburgers for lunch. We kept getting in line over and over again until we had enough hamburgers for the rest of the guys in guns. Came back and no one even knew we were gone.<br><br>
He was the one that took monopoly money down to mamason and convinced her it was real US currency. Once she accepted it, we all went down and bought all kinds of souvenier stuff, boy was Captain Robb pissed off. <br><br>
We called him tired Aggie, cause he walked and talked slow, but when once that first round was fired he was there at my side. I would like to see him again. But Iĺm afraid that if heĺs not in jail he might be dead. But then again he might be thinking the same about me.<br><br>
Shortly after Aggie got send to the rear to catch his flight back home, we got hit bad at a bend in the road on highway 4. It was in April 1968, Charlie Company had taken a beating, and I had gotten separated from the Marines in my company and ended up fighting along side of them. Just before dusk, when we were almost out of ammo, an amtrack shows up and a lone marine is standing up with hundreds of machine gun rounds draped across his chest and in ammo boxes. <br><br>
It was tired Aggie. We asked him he was doing out there in the boonies, since he was already suppose to be in DaNang and on his way back to the states. He said, ĹWell, I heard you guys needed ammo.ö<br><br>
I sure miss that guy.<br><br>
